### OpenTofu Version

```shell
OpenTofu v1.9.0
on linux_amd64
```

### OpenTofu Configuration Files

```hcl
terraform {
  required_providers {
    kubernetes = {
      source  = "hashicorp/kubernetes"
      version = "~> 2.35"
    }
  }
}

provider "kubernetes" {
  config_path    = "/home/<path>/kind.kubeconfig"
  config_context = "kind"
}

# to show this with easy configuration this is a secret
# but pretend this is a custom resource definition that has a controller that creates the secret that will be read later
resource "kubernetes_manifest" "crd" {
  manifest = {
    apiVersion = "v1"
    kind       = "Secret"
    metadata = {
      name = "my-secret"
      namespace = "default"
      # added later, this will cause the plan to fail
      # labels = {
      #   "app" = "second-apply"
      # }
    }
    data = {
      host = base64encode(yamldecode(file("${path.module}/<path>/kind.kubeconfig")).clusters[0].cluster["server"])
      ca_certificate = base64encode(yamldecode(file("${path.module}/<path>/kind.kubeconfig")).clusters[0].cluster["certificate-authority-data"])
      client_certificate = base64encode(yamldecode(file("${path.module}/<path>/kind.kubeconfig")).users[0].user["client-certificate-data"])
      client_key = base64encode(yamldecode(file("${path.module}/<path>/kind.kubeconfig")).users[0].user["client-key-data"])
    }
  }
}

data "kubernetes_secret_v1" "crd_secret" {
  metadata {
    name = "my-secret"
    namespace = "default"
  }
  depends_on = [
    kubernetes_manifest.crd
  ]
}

provider "kubernetes" {
  alias = "second"
  host                   = data.kubernetes_secret_v1.crd_secret.data.host
  cluster_ca_certificate = base64decode(data.kubernetes_secret_v1.crd_secret.data.ca_certificate)
  client_certificate     = base64decode(data.kubernetes_secret_v1.crd_secret.data.client_certificate)
  client_key             = base64decode(data.kubernetes_secret_v1.crd_secret.data.client_key)
}

resource "kubernetes_secret_v1" "test" {
  provider = kubernetes.second
  metadata {
    name = "test"
    namespace = "default"
  }
  data = {
    password = "my-password"
  }
}
```


### Debug Output

(I can add them if wanted, but its ~1500 lines because the kubernetes provider spams logs :) )

### Expected Behavior

Suppose I have the following sample program (see on top), which creates a CRD with the kubernetes provider (could be every other resource, not only kubernetes ones but its a good example to show this. In my demo I created the actual secret for demo purposes). The CRD controller then creates a secret in the background when processing the CRD (e.g. the CRD is a "cluster" resource and the controller adds the secret for the kubeconfig). If this secret contains data that a provider should use, the secret data source of the Kubernetes provider can be helpful. After successful read, the provider can be configured and used (in this case also the Kubernetes provider for demo purposes).

I would expect that using a data source in a provider configuration works and would result in resources than can be planned only during apply or something like that? I'm not quite in the Tofu code, maybe thats possible, if not I am open to further suggestions.

Maybe this could be solved with fallback for data sources (see #2443) but I think its not the best solution for this.

### Actual Behavior

This will work for the first apply. For any further applys or plans where something changes in the CRD (in my case I just added a label to the secret in the kubernetes_manifest resource), this no longer works because the data source can now only be read at runtime (because of the `depends_on`). The provider will use the default values (in case of the kubernetes provider its "localhost:443") which wont work.

### Steps to Reproduce

1. `tofu init`
2. `tofu apply` (works on first apply)
3. Change something in the first resource so that the data source must be re-read (e.g. add a label)
4. `tofu plan` (fails because provider is not configured)

### Additional Context

This was discussed initially in #2443, but I think this is an issue on its own but maybe this can be "solved" with the idea of fallback for data sources suggest in the issue. But I think the better way of solving this is to adjust how the plan of such resources works. 

### References

- #2443

