Thank you @apparentlymart and @simonostendorf for the comments and taking the time to read through the feature request.

---

## Handling of Different Error Types

> [...]
> With the protocol as it currently exists, the closest we could get to meeting this proposal would be to "fallback from state" on any error whatsoever.

Yes I thought so, thanks for clarifying.

It might not be desirable to always fallback to the last state if an error occurs. For example if the underlying provider does not find a given requested resource it is expected to return an error and fail the plan/apply. Falling back to the last successful state in this case could cause confusion and might not be intended.

I see a few ways this could be handled:

### Error Filter Pattern

We could try to determine the kind of failure from the error message by looking at specific keywords like "not found" and allow to set those with an `error_filter_pattern` as part of the `lifecycle -> fallback` hook.

```hcl
data "aws_ami" "example" {
  id = var.aws_ami_id

  lifecycle {
    fallback {
		enabled = true
   	 	error_filter_pattern = ["5[0-9]{2}|timeout"]
	}
  }
}
``` 

This would bypass the need to extend the provider interface while still allowing the user of the data source to configure the cases where they want to fallback.

### Circuit Breaker

In addition or as its own feature we could add a "circuit breaker" like pattern into the reading of data sources.
Every time a fallback was triggered and the apply succeeded the circuit breaker count is increased by one. On a configurable threshold the circuit breaker flips open and the reading of the data source fails. Once triggered it can only be closed again if the data source read was successful and an successful apply happened, thus valid new state was written. The counter would reset to 0 on every successful apply of the data source.

```hcl
data "aws_ami" "example" {
  id = var.aws_ami_id

  lifecycle {
    fallback {
		enabled = true
   	 	max_failures = 3 # default
	}
  }
}
```

---

## Fallback in Case of Schema Upgrades

> Your proposal would effectively cause the same situation to arise as part of the main plan/apply workflow, and so we'd need to define what ought to happen if the provider's ReadDataSource function returns an error and the prior state contains data that doesn't conform to the current provider schema.

I would say that in this case we could simply fail and have the error from the `ReadDataSource` passed through together with an additional warning message giving a reasoning to the user why the fallback was not triggered.

Another option I could see is that we can provide one of the following additional arguments to the `fallback` lifecycle:

- `unsafe_ignore_schema_changes = true` - always returns the last state and completely ignores schema changes then refreshes the state when the provider is called successfully the next time.
- `return_null_on_schema_changes = true` - returns `null` for the data source in case of a schema change.

We could also introduce an enum and different strategies for handling those cases making it more flexible:

```hcl
data "aws_ami" "example" {
  id = var.aws_ami_id

  lifecycle {
    fallback {
		enabled = true
   	 	schema_upgrade_stategy = RETRY|IGNORE|RETURN_NULL|FAIL(default)
	}
  }
}
```

---

@simonostendorf if I understand your use-case correctly you pretty much want to always fallback to the first and only state of the data source as it will never again come back "online"?

If this is correct it might make sense to not have something like a strategy for the overall fallback as well?

```hcl
[...]
data "kubernetes_secret_v1" "crd_secret" {
  metadata {
    name = "my-secret"
    namespace = "default"
  }
  depends_on = [
    kubernetes_manifest.crd
  ]
  lifecycle {
    fallback {
      enabled = true
      strategy = ALWAYS|RETRY|CIRCUIT_BREAKER|ONCE
    }
  }
}
[...]
```

---

Thank you all for your thoughts and the great discussion!

