This is a prototype for an idea I discussed in the comments of https://github.com/opentofu/opentofu/issues/2417.

The original design for check blocks was a boolean argument `condition` which returns true for valid and false for invalid, and then a separate string argument `error_message` whose value is displayed as part of an error diagnostic if the value is found to be invalid:

```hcl
variable "ami_id" {
  type = string

  validation {
    condition     = startswith(var.ami_id "ami-")
    error_message = "Must be a valid AMI ID, with the \"ami-\" prefix."
  }
  # (multiple validation blocks are allowed if there are multiple
  # independent rules to check. They must all pass for the
  # value to be considered valid.)
}
```

That design has worked well for simple primitive-typed variables, but it's annoying for variables of collection types because in that case we typically want to apply a validation rule to each element and then mention in the error messages exactly which elements were invalid, which requires both a complicated `condition` expression _and_ a very similar complicated `error_message` expression to repeat essentially the same steps to find out which elements were invalid:

```hcl
variable "ami_ids" {
  type = set(string)

  validation {
    condition = alltrue([
      for id in var.ami_ids : startswith(id, "ami-")
    ])
    error_message = "Invalid AMI IDs: ${join(", ", [
        for id in var.ami_ids : id if !startswith(id, "ami-")
    ])}."
  }
}

```

This change is a prototype for an optional new alternative where the block contains only a single argument `error_messages` that deals with both the condition and the error message generation at the same time. Its expression must return a list of strings where an empty list represents "valid" and a non-empty list represents "invalid". In the invalid case, each element is returned as a separate error diagnostic.

This means that module authors can use a "for" expression with an "if" clause to filter out all of the valid elements and to project any invalid elements into an error messages describing what is wrong with them. For example:

```hcl
variable "ami_ids" {
  type = set(string)

  validation {
    error_messages = [
      for id in var.ami_ids : format("Invalid AMI ID %q: must have \"ami-\" prefix.", id)
      if !startswith(id, "ami-")
    ]
  }
  # (multiple validation blocks are still allowed, and each one
  # can decide between condition+error_message or error_messages
  # as appropriate for what they are checking.)
}
```

In principle this could also be used with new provider-defined functions that are designed to take a value and return a list of problems with that value, such as in a hypothetical provider that implements JSON schema-based validation of a data structure using an externally-provided schema, as described in https://github.com/opentofu/opentofu/issues/2417#issuecomment-2611055522.

This is only a prototype so the test coverage is rudimentary and it only currently works for input variable validation. If we decide that we'd like to implement something like this for real then we'll want to extend it to work for all of the other kinds of checks -- test assertions, "check" block assertions, and preconditions/postconditions -- since the language design intent is for those to all appear to have essentially the same treatment, despite not all of the code currently being shared between them.

