Hi @shira-lev. Thank you for trying that!

Before trying anything else I'd like to try to understand why that solution didn't work, since that will hopefully provide a clue as to what we can try next.

With the explicit, fully-qualified source address in `cdktf.json`, did the generated `cdk.tf.json` change? Specifically, I was hoping that the `required_providers` part would change to appear something like this:

```json
    "required_providers": {
      "aws": {
        "source": "registry.opentofu.org/hashicorp/aws",
        "version": "5.51.1"
      }
    }
```

Does the generated `source` address now match the fully-qualified source address you added in `cdktf.json`?

@abstractionfactory understandable decision and I think you addressed one main point, namely JSON schemas.

We are currently working on a CLI to make the import of existing infrastructure setups easier for our customers (https://github.com/SAP/terraform-exporter-btp). In this CLI we leverage the `tfexec` functionality. However the only reason for using `tfexec` is that this way we get back the Terraform state in a typed way and can process the contained information easier i.e., with less overhead on our end. As we want to support OpenTofu we have been looking for an comparable option at OpenTofu.
Hence, if OpenTofu could provide e.g.,  a JSON schema for the state (which should be compatible as a dropIn replacement for Terraform) this would be great and address the main reason why we used `tfexec` and would make our life easier

